# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:engine/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:engine/adiabatic-quantum-motor] An **adiabatic quantum motor** is a mechanical device, typically nanometric, driven by a flux of quantum particles and able to perform cyclic motions.
[src:engine/adiabatic-quantum-motor] The adjective "adiabatic" in this context refers to the limit when the dynamics of the mechanical degrees of freedom is slow compared with the dwell time of the particles passing through the device.
[src:engine/adiabatic-quantum-motor] In this regime, it is commonly assumed that the mechanical degrees of freedom behave classically.
[src:engine/adiabatic-quantum-motor] This class of devices works essentially as quantum pumps operated in reverse.
[src:engine/adiabatic-quantum-motor] While in a quantum pump, the periodic movement of some parameters pumps quantum particles from one reservoir to another, in a quantum motor a DC current of particles induces the cyclic motion of the device.
[src:engine/adiabatic-quantum-motor] One key feature of these motors is that quantum interferences can be used to increase their efficiency by enhancing the reflection coefficient of the scattered particles.
[src:engine/adiabatic-quantum-motor] Although there are several proposals for the realization of adiabatic quantum motors, none of them have been verified experimentally.
[src:engine/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:engine/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:engine/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:engine/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:engine/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:engine/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:engine/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:engine/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:engine/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:engine/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:engine/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:engine/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:engine/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:engine/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:engine/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:engine/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:engine/aerodynamic] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:engine/aerodynamic] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:engine/air-quality] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:engine/air-quality] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:engine/air-quality] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:engine/air-quality] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:engine/air-quality] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:engine/air-quality] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:engine/air-quality] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:engine/air-quality] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:engine/air-quality] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:engine/air-quality] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:engine/air-quality] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:engine/air-quality] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:engine/air-quality] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:engine/air-quality] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] An **airbreathing jet engine** (or **ducted jet engine**) is a jet engine in which the exhaust gas which supplies jet propulsion is atmospheric air, which is taken in, compressed, heated, and expanded back to atmospheric pressure through a propelling nozzle.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Compression may be provided by a gas turbine, as in the original turbojet and newer turbofan, or arise solely from the ram pressure of the vehicle's velocity, as with the ramjet and pulsejet.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] All practical airbreathing jet engines heat the air by burning fuel.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Alternatively a heat exchanger may be used, as in a nuclear-powered jet engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Most modern jet engines are turbofans, which are more fuel efficient than turbojets because the thrust supplied by the gas turbine is augmented by bypass air passing through a ducted fan.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The original air-breathing gas turbine jet engine was the turbojet.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It was a concept brought to life by two engineers, Frank Whittle in England UK and Hans von Ohain in Germany.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The turbojet compresses and heats air and then exhausts it as a high speed, high temperature jet to create thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] While these engines are capable of giving high thrust levels, they are most efficient at very high speeds (over Mach 1), due to the low-mass-flow, high speed nature of the jet exhaust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Modern turbofans are a development of the turbojet; they are basically turbojets that include a new section called the *fan stage*.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Rather than using all their exhaust gases to provide direct thrust like a turbojet, turbofan engines extract some of the power from the exhaust gases inside the engine and use it to power the fan stage.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The fan stage accelerates a large volume of air through a duct, bypassing the *engine core* (the actual gas turbine component of the engine), and expelling it at the rear as a jet, creating thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A proportion of the air that comes through the fan stage enters the engine core rather than being ducted to the rear, and is thus compressed and heated; some of the energy is extracted to power the compressors and fans, while the remainder is exhausted at the rear.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This high-speed, hot-gas exhaust blends with the low speed, cool-air exhaust from the fan stage, and both contribute to the overall thrust of the engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Depending on what proportion of cool air is bypassed around the engine core, a turbofan can be called *low-bypass*, *high-bypass*, or *very-high-bypass* engines.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Over the last several decades, there has been a move towards *very high bypass* engines, which use fans far larger than the engine core itself, which is typically a modern, high efficiency two or three-spool design.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Airbreathing jet engines are nearly always internal combustion engines that obtain propulsion from the combustion of fuel inside the engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Oxygen present in the atmosphere is used to oxidise a fuel source, typically a hydrocarbon-based jet fuel.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The burning mixture expands greatly in volume, driving heated air through a propelling nozzle.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Two engineers, Frank Whittle in the UK and Hans von Ohain in Germany, developed the **turbojet** concept independently into practical engines during the late 1930s.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets consist of an inlet, a compressor, a combustor, a turbine (that drives the compressor) and a propelling nozzle.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets have a low propulsive efficiency below about Mach 2 and produce a lot of jet noise, both a result of the very high velocity of the exhaust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Modern jet propelled aircraft are powered by turbofans.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] These engines, with their lower exhaust velocities, produce less jet noise and use less fuel.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets are still used to power medium range cruise missiles due to their high exhaust speed, low frontal area, which reduces drag, and relative simplicity, which reduces cost.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The low pressure compressor (LPC), usually known as a fan, compresses air into a bypass duct whilst its inner portion supercharges the core compressor.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The fan is often an integral part of a multi-stage core LPC.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The bypass airflow either passes to a separate 'cold nozzle' or mixes with low pressure turbine exhaust gases, before expanding through a 'mixed flow nozzle'.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In the 1960s there was little difference between civil and military jet engines, apart from the use of afterburning in some (supersonic) applications.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Today, turbofans are used for airliners because they have an exhaust speed that is better matched to the subsonic flight speed of the airliner.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] At airliner flight speeds, the exhaust speed from a turbojet engine is excessively high and wastes energy.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The lower exhaust speed from a turbofan gives better fuel consumption.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The increased airflow from the fan gives higher thrust at low speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The lower exhaust speed also gives much lower jet noise.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The comparatively large frontal fan has several effects.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Compared to a turbojet of identical thrust, a turbofan has a much larger air mass flow rate and the flow through the bypass duct generates a significant fraction of the thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The additional duct air has not been ignited, which gives it a slow speed, but no extra fuel is needed to provide this thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Instead, the energy is taken from the central core, which gives it also a reduced exhaust speed.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The average velocity of the mixed exhaust air is thus reduced (low specific thrust) which is less wasteful of energy but reduces the top speed.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Overall, a turbofan can be much more fuel efficient and quieter, and it turns out that the fan also allows greater net thrust to be available at slow speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Thus civil turbofans today have a low exhaust speed (low *specific thrust* – net thrust divided by airflow) to keep jet noise to a minimum and to improve fuel efficiency.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Consequently, the bypass ratio (bypass flow divided by core flow) is relatively high (ratios from 4:1 up to 8:1 are common), with the Rolls-Royce Trent XWB approaching 10:1.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Only a single fan stage is required, because a low specific thrust implies a low fan pressure ratio.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbofans designed for subsonic civilian aircraft also usually have a just a single front fan, because their additional thrust is generated by a large additional mass of air which is only moderately compressed, rather than a smaller amount of air which is greatly compressed.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Military turbofans, however, have a relatively high specific thrust, to maximize the thrust for a given frontal area, jet noise being of less concern in military uses relative to civil uses.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Multistage fans are normally needed to reach the relatively high fan pressure ratio needed for high specific thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although high turbine inlet temperatures are often employed, the bypass ratio tends to be low, usually significantly less than 2.0.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboprop engines are jet engine derivatives, still gas turbines, that extract work from the hot-exhaust jet to turn a rotating shaft, which is then used to produce thrust by some other means.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] While not strictly jet engines in that they rely on an auxiliary mechanism to produce thrust, turboprops are very similar to other turbine-based jet engines, and are often described as such.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In turboprop engines, a portion of the engine's thrust is produced by spinning a propeller, rather than relying solely on high-speed jet exhaust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Producing thrust both ways, turboprops are occasionally referred to as a type of hybrid jet engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They differ from turbofans in that a traditional propeller, rather than a ducted fan, provides the majority of thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Most turboprops use gear-reduction between the turbine and the propeller.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] (Geared turbofans also feature gear reduction, but they are less common.) The hot-jet exhaust is an important minority of thrust, and maximum thrust is obtained by matching the two thrust contributions.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboprops generally have better performance than turbojets or turbofans at low speeds where propeller efficiency is high, but become increasingly noisy and inefficient at high speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboshaft engines are very similar to turboprops, differing in that nearly all energy in the exhaust is extracted to spin the rotating shaft, which is used to power machinery rather than a propeller, they therefore generate little to no jet thrust and are often used to power helicopters.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A propfan engine (also called a "propjet", "unducted fan", "open rotor", or "ultra-high bypass") is a jet engine that uses its gas generator to power an exposed fan, similar to turboprop engines.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Like turboprop engines, propfans generate most of their thrust from the propeller and not the exhaust jet.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The primary difference between turboprop and propfan design is that the propeller blades on a propfan are highly swept to allow them to operate at speeds around Mach 0.8, which is competitive with modern commercial turbofans.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] These engines have the fuel efficiency advantages of turboprops with the performance capability of commercial turbofans.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] While significant research and testing (including flight testing) has been conducted on propfans, none have entered production.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The various components named above have constraints on how they are put together to generate the most efficiency or performance.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The performance and efficiency of an engine can never be taken in isolation; for example fuel/distance efficiency of a supersonic jet engine maximises at about Mach 2, whereas the drag for the vehicle carrying it is increasing as a square law and has much extra drag in the transonic region.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The highest fuel efficiency for the overall vehicle is thus typically around Mach 0.85.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The thermodynamics of a typical air-breathing jet engine are modeled approximately by a **Brayton Cycle** which is a thermodynamic cycle that describes the workings of the gas turbine engine, which is the basis of the airbreathing jet engine and others.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is named after George Brayton (1830–1892), the American engineer who developed it, although it was originally proposed and patented by Englishman John Barber in 1791.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is also sometimes known as the **Joule cycle**.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The nominal net thrust quoted for a jet engine usually refers to the Sea Level Static (SLS) condition, either for the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) or a hot day condition (e.g.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] As an example, the GE90-76B has a take-off static thrust of 76,000 lbf (360 kN) at SLS, ISA+15 °C.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Naturally, net thrust will decrease with altitude, because of the lower air density.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] There is also, however, a flight speed effect.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Initially as the aircraft gains speed down the runway, there will be little increase in nozzle pressure and temperature, because the ram rise in the intake is very small.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] There will also be little change in mass flow.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Consequently, nozzle gross thrust initially only increases marginally with flight speed.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, being an air breathing engine (unlike a conventional rocket) there is a penalty for taking on-board air from the atmosphere.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although the penalty is zero at static conditions, it rapidly increases with flight speed, causing the net thrust to be eroded.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] As flight speed builds up after take-off, the ram rise in the intake starts to have a significant effect upon nozzle pressure/temperature and intake airflow, causing nozzle gross thrust to climb more rapidly.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This term now starts to offset the still increasing ram drag, eventually causing net thrust to start to increase.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In some engines, the net thrust at say Mach 1.0, sea level can even be slightly greater than the static thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Above Mach 1.0, with a subsonic inlet design, shock losses tend to decrease net thrust, however a suitably designed supersonic inlet can give a lower reduction in intake pressure recovery, allowing net thrust to continue to climb in the supersonic regime.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines are usually very reliable and have a very good safety record.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In some cases in jet engines the conditions in the engine due to airflow entering the engine or other variations can cause the compressor blades to stall.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] When this occurs the pressure in the engine blows out past the blades, and the stall is maintained until the pressure has decreased, and the engine has lost all thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The compressor blades will then usually come out of stall, and re-pressurize the engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] If conditions are not corrected, the cycle will usually repeat.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Depending on the engine this can be highly damaging to the engine and creates worrying vibrations for the crew.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Fan, compressor or turbine blade failures have to be contained within the engine casing.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] To do this the engine has to be designed to pass blade containment tests as specified by certification authorities.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Bird ingestion is the term used when birds enter the intake of a jet engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is a common aircraft safety hazard and has caused fatal accidents.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 1988 an Ethiopian Airlines Boeing 737 ingested pigeons into both engines during take-off and then crashed in an attempt to return to the Bahir Dar airport; of the 104 people aboard, 35 died and 21 were injured.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In another incident in 1995, a Dassault Falcon 20 crashed at a Paris airport during an emergency landing attempt after ingesting lapwings into an engine, which caused an engine failure and a fire in the airplane fuselage; all 10 people on board were killed.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines have to be designed to withstand the ingestion of birds of a specified weight and number, and to not lose more than a specified amount of thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The weight and numbers of birds that can be ingested without hazarding the safe flight of the aircraft are related to the engine intake area.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 2009, an Airbus A320 aircraft, US Airways Flight 1549, ingested one Canada goose into each engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The plane ditched in the Hudson River after taking off from LaGuardia International Airport in New York City.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The incident illustrated the hazards of ingesting birds beyond the "designed-for" limit.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The outcome of an ingestion event and whether it causes an accident, be it on a small fast plane, such as military jet fighters, or a large transport, depends on the number and weight of birds and where they strike the fan blade span or the nose cone.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Core damage usually results with impacts near the blade root or on the nose cone.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Few birds fly high, so the greatest risk of a bird ingestion is during takeoff and landing and during low level flying.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] If a jet plane is flying through air contaminated with volcanic ash, there is risk that ingested ash will cause erosion damage to the compressor blades, blockage of fuel nozzle air holes and blockage of the turbine cooling passages.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Some of these effects may cause the engine to surge or flame-out during the flight.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Re-lights are usually successful after flame-outs but with considerable loss of altitude.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It was the case of British Airways Flight 9 which flew through volcanic dust at 37,000 ft.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] All 4 engines flamed out and re-light attempts were successful at about 13,000 ft.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] One class of failure that has caused accidents is the uncontained failure, where rotating parts of the engine break off and exit through the case.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] These high energy parts can cut fuel and control lines, and can penetrate the cabin.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although fuel and control lines are usually duplicated for reliability, the crash of United Airlines Flight 232 was caused when hydraulic fluid lines for all three independent hydraulic systems were simultaneously severed by shrapnel from an uncontained engine failure.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Prior to the United 232 crash, the probability of a simultaneous failure of all three hydraulic systems was considered as high as a billion-to-one.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, the statistical models used to come up with this figure did not account for the fact that the number-two engine was mounted at the tail close to all the hydraulic lines, nor the possibility that an engine failure would release fragments in multiple directions.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Since then, more modern aircraft engine designs have focused on keeping shrapnel from penetrating the cowling or ductwork, and have increasingly utilized high-strength composite materials to achieve the required penetration resistance while keeping the weight low.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 2007 the cost of jet fuel, while highly variable from one airline to another, averaged 26.5% of total operating costs, making it the single largest operating expense for most airlines.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines are usually run on fossil fuels and are thus a source of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines can also run on biofuels or hydrogen, although hydrogen is usually produced from fossil fuels.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] About 7.2% of the oil used in 2004 was consumed by jet engines.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Some scientists believe that jet engines are also a source of global dimming due to the water vapour in the exhaust causing cloud formations.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Nitrogen compounds are also formed during the combustion process from reactions with atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] At low altitudes this is not thought to be especially harmful, but for supersonic aircraft that fly in the stratosphere some destruction of ozone may occur.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Sulphates are also emitted if the fuel contains sulphur.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A ramjet is a form of airbreathing jet engine using the engine's forward motion to compress incoming air, without a rotary compressor.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets cannot produce thrust at zero airspeed and thus cannot move an aircraft from a standstill.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets require considerable forward speed to operate well, and as a class work most efficiently at speeds around Mach 3.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This type of jet can operate up to speeds of Mach 6.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They consist of three sections; an inlet to compress incoming air, a combustor to inject and combust fuel, and a nozzle to expel the hot gases and produce thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets require a relatively high speed to efficiently compress the incoming air, so ramjets cannot operate at a standstill and they are most efficient at supersonic speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A key trait of ramjet engines is that combustion is done at subsonic speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The supersonic incoming air is dramatically slowed through the inlet, where it is then combusted at the much slower, subsonic, speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The faster the incoming air is, however, the less efficient it becomes to slow it to subsonic speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Therefore, ramjet engines are limited to approximately Mach 5.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They have also been used successfully, though not efficiently, as tip jets on helicopter rotors.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Pulsejets are subsonic engines which also use ram compression, but with intermittent combustion unlike the continuous combustion used in a ramjet.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They are a quite distinct type of jet engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Scramjets are an evolution of ramjets that are able to operate at much higher speeds than any other kind of airbreathing engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They share a similar structure with ramjets, being a specially shaped tube that compresses air with no moving parts through ram-air compression.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] They consist of an inlet, a combustor, and a nozzle.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The primary difference between ramjets and scramjets is that scramjets do not slow the oncoming airflow to subsonic speeds for combustion.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Thus, scramjets do not have the diffuser required by ramjets to slow the incoming airflow to subsonic speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Scramjets start working at speeds of at least Mach 4, and have a maximum useful speed of approximately Mach 17.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Due to aerodynamic heating at these high speeds, cooling poses a challenge to engineers.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Since scramjets use supersonic combustion they can operate at speeds above Mach 6 where traditional ramjets are too inefficient.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Very few scramjet engines have ever been built and flown.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In May 2010 the Boeing X-51 set the endurance record for the longest scramjet burn at over 200 seconds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojet operation over the complete flight envelope from zero to Mach 3+ requires features to allow the compressor to function properly at the high inlet temperatures beyond Mach 2.5 as well as at low flight speeds.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The J58 compressor solution was to bleed airflow from the 4th compressor stage at speeds above about Mach 2.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The bleed flow, 20% at Mach 3, was returned to the engine via 6 external tubes to cool the afterburner liner and primary nozzle as well as to provide extra air for combustion.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The J58 engine was the only operational turbojet engine, being designed to operate continuously even at maximum afterburning, for Mach 3.2 cruise.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] An alternative solution is seen in a contemporary installation, which did not reach operational status, the Mach 3 GE YJ93/XB-70.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Yet another solution was specified in a proposal for a Mach 3 reconnaissance Phantom.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This was pre-compressor cooling, albeit available for relatively short duration.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines can be run on almost any fuel.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Hydrogen is a highly desirable fuel, as, although the energy per mole is not unusually high, the molecule is very much lighter than other molecules.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The energy per kg of hydrogen is twice that of more common fuels and this gives twice the specific impulse.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In addition, jet engines running on hydrogen are quite easy to build—the first ever turbojet was run on hydrogen.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Also, although not duct engines, hydrogen-fueled rocket engines have seen extensive use.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, in almost every other way, hydrogen is problematic.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The downside of hydrogen is its density; in gaseous form the tanks are impractical for flight, but even in the form of liquid hydrogen it has a density one fourteenth that of water.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is also deeply cryogenic and requires very significant insulation that precludes it being stored in wings.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The overall vehicle would end up being very large, and difficult for most airports to accommodate.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Finally, pure hydrogen is not found in nature, and must be manufactured either via steam reforming or expensive electrolysis.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] A few experimental hydrogen-powered aircraft have flown with propellers, and jets have been proposed that may be feasible.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Carmichael in 1955 is that hydrogen-fueled engines could theoretically have much higher performance than hydrocarbon-fueled engines if a heat exchanger were used to cool the incoming air.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The low temperature allows lighter materials to be used, a higher mass-flow through the engines, and permits combustors to inject more fuel without overheating the engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This idea leads to plausible designs like Reaction Engines SABRE, that might permit single-stage-to-orbit launch vehicles, and ATREX, which could permit jet engines to be used up to hypersonic speeds and high altitudes for boosters for launch vehicles.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The idea is also being researched by the EU for a concept to achieve non-stop antipodal supersonic passenger travel at Mach 5 (Reaction Engines A2).
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] There are different types of air turborockets.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and others.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] In multiple cases, instead of expressing rotor speeds (N1, N2) as RPM on cockpit displays, pilots are provided with the speeds expressed as a percentage of the design point speed.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] For example, at full power, the N1 might be 101.5% or 100%.
[src:engine/airbreathing-jet-engine] This user interface decision has been made as a human factors consideration, since pilots are more likely to notice a problem with a two- or 3-digit percentage (where 100% implies a nominal value) than with a 5-digit RPM.
[src:engine/engine] An **engine** or **motor** is a machine designed to convert one or more forms of energy into mechanical energy.
[src:engine/engine] Available energy sources include potential energy (e.g. energy of the Earth's gravitational field as exploited in hydroelectric power generation), heat energy (e.g. geothermal), chemical energy, electric potential and nuclear energy (from nuclear fission or nuclear fusion).
[src:engine/engine] Many of these processes generate heat as an intermediate energy form; thus heat engines have special importance.
[src:engine/engine] Some natural processes, such as atmospheric convection cells convert environmental heat into motion (e.g. in the form of rising air currents).
[src:engine/engine] Mechanical energy is of particular importance in transportation, but also plays a role in many industrial processes such as cutting, grinding, crushing, and mixing.
[src:engine/engine] Mechanical heat engines convert heat into work via various thermodynamic processes.
[src:engine/engine] The internal combustion engine is perhaps the most common example of a mechanical heat engine in which heat from the combustion of a fuel causes rapid pressurisation of the gaseous combustion products in the combustion chamber, causing them to expand and drive a piston, which turns a crankshaft.
[src:engine/engine] Unlike internal combustion engines, a reaction engine (such as a jet engine) produces thrust by expelling reaction mass, in accordance with Newton's third law of motion.
[src:engine/engine] Apart from heat engines, electric motors convert electrical energy into mechanical motion, pneumatic motors use compressed air, and clockwork motors in wind-up toys use elastic energy.
[src:engine/engine] In biological systems, molecular motors, like myosins in muscles, use chemical energy to create forces and ultimately motion (a chemical engine, but not a heat engine).
[src:engine/engine] Chemical heat engines which employ air (ambient atmospheric gas) as a part of the fuel reaction are regarded as airbreathing engines.
[src:engine/engine] All chemically fueled heat engines emit exhaust gases.
[src:engine/engine] Strict zero-emissions generally means zero emissions other than water and water vapour.
[src:engine/engine] Only heat engines which combust pure hydrogen (fuel) and pure oxygen (oxidizer) achieve zero-emission by a strict definition (in practice, some rocket engines).
[src:engine/engine] If hydrogen is burnt in combination with air (all airbreathing engines), a side reaction between atmospheric oxygen and atmospheric nitrogen produces small amounts of NO*x*.
[src:engine/engine] If a hydrocarbon (such as alcohol or gasoline) is burnt as fuel, CO2, a greenhouse gas, is emitted.
[src:engine/engine] Hydrogen and oxygen can also be made to react and form water in a fuel cell without producing NO*x*, but a fuel cell is a type of electrochemical device, not a heat engine.
[src:engine/engine] The word *engine* derives from Old French *engin*, from the Latin *ingenium*–the root of the word *ingenious*.
[src:engine/engine] Pre-industrial weapons of war, such as catapults, trebuchets and battering rams, were called *siege engines*, and knowledge of how to construct them was often treated as a military secret.
[src:engine/engine] The word *gin*, as in *cotton gin*, is short for *engine*.
[src:engine/engine] Most mechanical devices invented during the Industrial Revolution were described as engines—the steam engine being a notable example.
[src:engine/engine] However, the original steam engines, such as those by Thomas Savery, were not mechanical engines but pumps.
[src:engine/engine] In this manner, a fire engine in its original form was merely a water pump, with the engine being transported to the fire by horses.
[src:engine/engine] In modern usage, the term *engine* typically describes devices, like steam engines and internal combustion engines, that burn or otherwise consume fuel to perform mechanical work by exerting a torque or linear force (usually in the form of thrust).
[src:engine/engine] Devices converting heat energy into motion are commonly referred to simply as *engines*.
[src:engine/engine] Examples of engines which exert a torque include the familiar automobile gasoline and diesel engines, as well as turboshafts.
[src:engine/engine] Examples of engines which produce thrust include turbofans and rockets.
[src:engine/engine] When the internal combustion engine was invented, the term *motor* was initially used to distinguish it from the steam engine—which was in wide use at the time, powering locomotives and other vehicles such as steam rollers.
[src:engine/engine] The term *motor* derives from the Latin noun *mōtor* which means 'that which moves something'.
[src:engine/engine] Thus a motor is a device that imparts motion.
[src:engine/engine] A heat engine may also serve as a *prime mover*—a component that transforms the flow or changes in pressure of a fluid into mechanical energy.
[src:engine/engine] An automobile powered by an internal combustion engine may make use of various motors and pumps, but ultimately all such devices derive their power from the engine.
[src:engine/engine] Simple machines, such as the club and oar (examples of the lever), are prehistoric.
[src:engine/engine] More complex engines using human power, animal power, water power, wind power and even steam power date back to antiquity.
[src:engine/engine] Human power was focused by the use of simple engines, such as the capstan, windlass or treadmill, and with ropes, pulleys, and block and tackle arrangements; this power was transmitted usually with the forces multiplied and the speed reduced.
[src:engine/engine] These were used in cranes and aboard ships in Ancient Greece, as well as in mines, water pumps and siege engines in Ancient Rome.
[src:engine/engine] The writers of those times, including Vitruvius, Frontinus and Pliny the Elder, treat these engines as commonplace, so their invention may be more ancient.
[src:engine/engine] By the 1st century AD, cattle and horses were used in mills, driving machines similar to those powered by humans in earlier times.
[src:engine/engine] According to Strabo, a water-powered mill was built in Kaberia of the kingdom of Mithridates during the 1st century BC.
[src:engine/engine] Use of water wheels in mills spread throughout the Roman Empire over the next few centuries.
[src:engine/engine] Some were quite complex, with aqueducts, dams, and sluices to maintain and channel the water, along with systems of gears, or toothed-wheels made of wood and metal to regulate the speed of rotation.
[src:engine/engine] More sophisticated small devices, such as the Antikythera Mechanism used complex trains of gears and dials to act as calendars or predict astronomical events.
[src:engine/engine] In a poem by Ausonius in the 4th century AD, he mentions a stone-cutting saw powered by water.
[src:engine/engine] Hero of Alexandria is credited with many such wind and steam powered machines in the 1st century AD, including the Aeolipile and the vending machine, often these machines were associated with worship, such as animated altars and automated temple doors.
[src:engine/engine] Medieval Muslim engineers employed gears in mills and water-raising machines, and used dams as a source of water power to provide additional power to watermills and water-raising machines.
[src:engine/engine] In the medieval Islamic world, such advances made it possible to mechanize many industrial tasks previously carried out by manual labour.
[src:engine/engine] In 1206, al-Jazari employed a crank-conrod system for two of his water-raising machines.
[src:engine/engine] A rudimentary steam turbine device was described by Taqi al-Din in 1551 and by Giovanni Branca in 1629.
[src:engine/engine] In the 13th century, the solid rocket motor was invented in China.
[src:engine/engine] Driven by gunpowder, this simplest form of internal combustion engine was unable to deliver sustained power, but was useful for propelling weaponry at high speeds towards enemies in battle and for fireworks.
[src:engine/engine] After invention, this innovation spread throughout Europe.
[src:engine/engine] The Watt steam engine was the first type of steam engine to make use of steam at a pressure just above atmospheric to drive the piston helped by a partial vacuum.
[src:engine/engine] Improving on the design of the 1712 Newcomen steam engine, the Watt steam engine, developed sporadically from 1763 to 1775, was a great step in the development of the steam engine.
[src:engine/engine] Offering a dramatic increase in fuel efficiency, James Watt's design became synonymous with steam engines, due in no small part to his business partner, Matthew Boulton.
[src:engine/engine] It enabled rapid development of efficient semi-automated factories on a previously unimaginable scale in places where waterpower was not available.
[src:engine/engine] Later development led to steam locomotives and great expansion of railway transportation.
[src:engine/engine] As for internal combustion piston engines, these were tested in France in 1807 by de Rivaz and independently, by the Niépce brothers.
[src:engine/engine] They were theoretically advanced by Carnot in 1824.
[src:engine/engine] In 1853–57 Eugenio Barsanti and Felice Matteucci invented and patented an engine using the free-piston principle that was possibly the first 4-cycle engine.
[src:engine/engine] The invention of an internal combustion engine which was later commercially successful was made during 1860 by Etienne Lenoir.
[src:engine/engine] In 1877, the Otto cycle was capable of giving a far higher power-to-weight ratio than steam engines and worked much better for many transportation applications such as cars and aircraft.
[src:engine/engine] The first commercially successful automobile, created by Karl Benz, added to the interest in light and powerful engines.
[src:engine/engine] The lightweight gasoline internal combustion engine, operating on a four-stroke Otto cycle, has been the most successful for light automobiles, while the thermally more-efficient Diesel engine is used for trucks and buses.
[src:engine/engine] However, in recent years, turbocharged Diesel engines have become increasingly popular in automobiles, especially outside of the United States, even for quite small cars.
[src:engine/engine] In 1897, Karl Benz was granted a patent for his design of the first engine with horizontally opposed pistons.
[src:engine/engine] His design created an engine in which the corresponding pistons move in horizontal cylinders and reach top dead center simultaneously, thus automatically balancing each other with respect to their individual momentum.
[src:engine/engine] Engines of this design are often referred to as “flat” or “boxer” engines due to their shape and low profile.
[src:engine/engine] They were used in the Volkswagen Beetle, the Citroën 2CV, some Porsche and Subaru cars, many BMW and Honda motorcycles.
[src:engine/engine] Opposed four- and six-cylinder engines continue to be used as a power source in small, propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:engine/engine] The continued use of internal combustion engines in automobiles is partly due to the improvement of engine control systems, such as on-board computers providing engine management processes, and electronically controlled fuel injection.
[src:engine/engine] Forced air induction by turbocharging and supercharging have increased the power output of smaller displacement engines that are lighter in weight and more fuel-efficient at normal cruise power.
[src:engine/engine] Similar changes have been applied to smaller Diesel engines, giving them almost the same performance characteristics as gasoline engines.
[src:engine/engine] This is especially evident with the popularity of smaller diesel engine-propelled cars in Europe.
[src:engine/engine] Diesel engines produce lower hydrocarbon and CO2 emissions, but greater particulate and NO*x* pollution, than gasoline engines.
[src:engine/engine] Diesel engines are also 40% more fuel efficient than comparable gasoline engines.
[src:engine/engine] In the first half of the 20th century, a trend of increasing engine power occurred, particularly in the U.S. models.
[src:engine/engine] Design changes incorporated all known methods of increasing engine capacity, including increasing the pressure in the cylinders to improve efficiency, increasing the size of the engine, and increasing the rate at which the engine produces work.
[src:engine/engine] The higher forces and pressures created by these changes created engine vibration and size problems that led to stiffer, more compact engines with V and opposed cylinder layouts replacing longer straight-line arrangements.
[src:engine/engine] Optimal combustion efficiency in passenger vehicles is reached with a coolant temperature of around 110 °C (230 °F).
[src:engine/engine] Earlier automobile engine development produced a much larger range of engines than is in common use today.
[src:engine/engine] Engines have ranged from 1- to 16-cylinder designs with corresponding differences in overall size, weight, engine displacement, and cylinder bores.
[src:engine/engine] Four cylinders and power ratings from 19 to 120 hp (14 to 90 kW) were followed in a majority of the models.
[src:engine/engine] Several three-cylinder, two-stroke-cycle models were built while most engines had straight or in-line cylinders.
[src:engine/engine] There were several V-type models and horizontally opposed two- and four-cylinder makes too.
[src:engine/engine] Overhead camshafts were frequently employed.
[src:engine/engine] The smaller engines were commonly air-cooled and located at the rear of the vehicle; compression ratios were relatively low.
[src:engine/engine] The 1970s and 1980s saw an increased interest in improved fuel economy, which caused a return to smaller V-6 and four-cylinder layouts, with as many as five valves per cylinder to improve efficiency.
[src:engine/engine] The Bugatti Veyron 16.4 operates with a W16 engine, meaning that two V8 cylinder layouts are positioned next to each other to create the W shape sharing the same crankshaft.
[src:engine/engine] The largest internal combustion engine ever built is the Wärtsilä-Sulzer RTA96-C, a 14-cylinder, 2-stroke turbocharged diesel engine that was designed to power the *Emma Mærsk*, the largest container ship in the world when launched in 2006.
[src:engine/engine] This engine has a mass of 2,300 tonnes, and when running at 102 rpm (1.7 Hz) produces over 80 MW, and can use up to 250 tonnes of fuel per day.
[src:engine/engine] An engine can be put into a category according to two criteria: the form of energy it accepts in order to create motion, and the type of motion it outputs.
[src:engine/engine] Combustion engines are heat engines driven by the heat of a combustion process.
[src:engine/engine] The *internal combustion engine* is an engine in which the combustion of a fuel (generally, fossil fuel) occurs with an oxidizer (usually air) in a combustion chamber.
[src:engine/engine] In an internal combustion engine the expansion of the high temperature and high pressure gases, which are produced by the combustion, directly applies force to components of the engine, such as the pistons or turbine blades or a nozzle, and by moving it over a distance, generates mechanical work.
[src:engine/engine] An *external combustion engine* (EC engine) is a heat engine where an internal working fluid is heated by combustion of an external source, through the engine wall or a heat exchanger.
[src:engine/engine] The fluid then, by expanding and acting on the mechanism of the engine produces motion and usable work.
[src:engine/engine] The fluid is then cooled, compressed and reused (closed cycle), or (less commonly) dumped, and cool fluid pulled in (open cycle air engine).
[src:engine/engine] "Combustion" refers to burning fuel with an oxidizer, to supply the heat.
[src:engine/engine] Engines of similar (or even identical) configuration and operation may use a supply of heat from other sources such as nuclear, solar, geothermal or exothermic reactions not involving combustion; but are not then strictly classed as external combustion engines, but as external thermal engines.
[src:engine/engine] The working fluid can be a gas as in a Stirling engine, or steam as in a steam engine or an organic liquid such as n-pentane in an Organic Rankine cycle.
[src:engine/engine] The fluid can be of any composition; gas is by far the most common, although even single-phase liquid is sometimes used.
[src:engine/engine] In the case of the steam engine, the fluid changes phases between liquid and gas.
[src:engine/engine] A continuous stream of air flows through the air-breathing engine.
[src:engine/engine] This air is compressed, mixed with fuel, ignited and expelled as the exhaust gas.
[src:engine/engine] In reaction engines, the majority of the combustion energy (heat) exits the engine as exhaust gas, which provides thrust directly.
[src:engine/engine] The operation of engines typically has a negative impact upon air quality and ambient sound levels.
[src:engine/engine] There has been a growing emphasis on the pollution producing features of automotive power systems.
[src:engine/engine] This has created new interest in alternate power sources and internal-combustion engine refinements.
[src:engine/engine] Though a few limited-production battery-powered electric vehicles have appeared, they have not proved competitive owing to costs and operating characteristics.
[src:engine/engine] In the 21st century the diesel engine has been increasing in popularity with automobile owners.
[src:engine/engine] However, the gasoline engine and the Diesel engine, with their new emission-control devices to improve emission performance, have not yet been significantly challenged.
[src:engine/engine] A number of manufacturers have introduced hybrid engines, mainly involving a small gasoline engine coupled with an electric motor and with a large battery bank, these are starting to become a popular option because of their environment awareness.
[src:engine/engine] Carbon monoxide is highly toxic, and can cause carbon monoxide poisoning, so it is important to avoid any build-up of the gas in a confined space.
[src:engine/engine] Catalytic converters can reduce toxic emissions, but not eliminate them.
[src:engine/engine] Also, resulting greenhouse gas emissions, chiefly carbon dioxide, from the widespread use of engines in the modern industrialized world is contributing to the global greenhouse effect – a primary concern regarding global warming.
[src:engine/engine] Some engines convert heat from noncombustive processes into mechanical work, for example a nuclear power plant uses the heat from the nuclear reaction to produce steam and drive a steam engine, or a gas turbine in a rocket engine may be driven by decomposing hydrogen peroxide.
[src:engine/engine] Apart from the different energy source, the engine is often engineered much the same as an internal or external combustion engine.
[src:engine/engine] Another group of noncombustive engines includes thermoacoustic heat engines (sometimes called "TA engines") which are thermoacoustic devices that use high-amplitude sound waves to pump heat from one place to another, or conversely use a heat difference to induce high-amplitude sound waves.
[src:engine/engine] In general, thermoacoustic engines can be divided into standing wave and travelling wave devices.
[src:engine/engine] Stirling engines can be another form of non-combustive heat engine.
[src:engine/engine] They use the Stirling thermodynamic cycle to convert heat into work.
[src:engine/engine] An example is the alpha type Stirling engine, whereby gas flows, via a recuperator, between a hot cylinder and a cold cylinder, which are attached to reciprocating pistons 90° out of phase.
[src:engine/engine] The gas receives heat at the hot cylinder and expands, driving the piston that turns the crankshaft.
[src:engine/engine] After expanding and flowing through the recuperator, the gas rejects heat at the cold cylinder and the ensuing pressure drop leads to its compression by the other (displacement) piston, which forces it back to the hot cylinder.
[src:engine/engine] Non-thermal motors usually are powered by a chemical reaction, but are not heat engines.
[src:engine/engine] An *electric motor* uses electrical energy to produce mechanical energy, usually through the interaction of magnetic fields and current-carrying conductors.
[src:engine/engine] The reverse process, producing electrical energy from mechanical energy, is accomplished by a generator or dynamo.
[src:engine/engine] Traction motors used on vehicles often perform both tasks.
[src:engine/engine] Electric motors can be run as generators and vice versa, although this is not always practical.
[src:engine/engine] Electric motors are ubiquitous, being found in applications as diverse as industrial fans, blowers and pumps, machine tools, household appliances, power tools, and disk drives.
[src:engine/engine] They may be powered by direct current (for example a battery powered portable device or motor vehicle), or by alternating current from a central electrical distribution grid.
[src:engine/engine] The smallest motors may be found in electric wristwatches.
[src:engine/engine] Medium-size motors of highly standardized dimensions and characteristics provide convenient mechanical power for industrial uses.
[src:engine/engine] The very largest electric motors are used for propulsion of large ships, and for such purposes as pipeline compressors, with ratings in the thousands of kilowatts.
[src:engine/engine] Electric motors may be classified by the source of electric power, by their internal construction, and by their application.
[src:engine/engine] The physical principle of production of mechanical force by the interactions of an electric current and a magnetic field was known as early as 1821.
[src:engine/engine] Electric motors of increasing efficiency were constructed throughout the 19th century, but commercial exploitation of electric motors on a large scale required efficient electrical generators and electrical distribution networks.
[src:engine/engine] To reduce the electric energy consumption from motors and their associated carbon footprints, various regulatory authorities in many countries have introduced and implemented legislation to encourage the manufacture and use of higher efficiency electric motors.
[src:engine/engine] A well-designed motor can convert over 90% of its input energy into useful power for decades.
[src:engine/engine] When the efficiency of a motor is raised by even a few percentage points, the savings, in kilowatt hours (and therefore in cost), are enormous.
[src:engine/engine] By convention, *electric engine* refers to a railroad electric locomotive, rather than an electric motor.
[src:engine/engine] Some motors are powered by potential or kinetic energy, for example some funiculars, gravity plane and ropeway conveyors have used the energy from moving water or rocks, and some clocks have a weight that falls under gravity.
[src:engine/engine] Other forms of potential energy include compressed gases (such as pneumatic motors), springs (clockwork motors) and elastic bands.
[src:engine/engine] Historic military siege engines included large catapults, trebuchets, and (to some extent) battering rams were powered by potential energy.
[src:engine/engine] A *pneumatic motor* is a machine that converts potential energy in the form of compressed air into mechanical work.
[src:engine/engine] Pneumatic motors generally convert the compressed air to mechanical work through either linear or rotary motion.
[src:engine/engine] Linear motion can come from either a diaphragm or a piston actuator, while rotary motion is supplied by either a vane type air motor or piston air motor.
[src:engine/engine] Pneumatic motors have found widespread success in the hand-held tool industry and continual attempts are being made to expand their use to the transportation industry.
[src:engine/engine] However, pneumatic motors must overcome efficiency deficiencies before being seen as a viable option in the transportation industry.
[src:engine/engine] A *hydraulic motor* derives its power from a pressurized liquid.
[src:engine/engine] This type of engine is used to move heavy loads and drive machinery.
[src:engine/engine] Some motor units can have multiple sources of energy.
[src:engine/engine] For example, a plug-in hybrid electric vehicle's electric motor could source electricity from either a battery or from fossil fuels inputs via an internal combustion engine and a generator.
[src:engine/engine] The following are used in the assessment of the performance of an engine.
[src:engine/engine] Speed refers to crankshaft rotation in piston engines and the speed of compressor/turbine rotors and electric motor rotors.
[src:engine/engine] It is typically measured in revolutions per minute (rpm).
[src:engine/engine] Thrust is the force exerted on an airplane as a consequence of its propeller or jet engine accelerating the air passing through it.
[src:engine/engine] It is also the force exerted on a ship as a consequence of its propeller accelerating the water passing through it.
[src:engine/engine] Torque is a turning moment on a shaft and is calculated by multiplying the force causing the moment by its distance from the shaft.
[src:engine/engine] Power is the measure of how fast work is done.
[src:engine/engine] Efficiency is a proportion of useful energy output compared to total input.
[src:engine/engine] Vehicle noise is predominantly from the engine at low vehicle speeds and from tires and the air flowing past the vehicle at higher speeds.
[src:engine/engine] Electric motors are quieter than internal combustion engines.
[src:engine/engine] Thrust-producing engines, such as turbofans, turbojets and rockets emit the greatest amount of noise due to the way their thrust-producing, high-velocity exhaust streams interact with the surrounding stationary air.
[src:engine/engine] Noise reduction technology includes intake and exhaust system mufflers (silencers) on gasoline and diesel engines and noise attenuation liners in turbofan inlets.
